{"cursor":"11694","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"'Systems psychology' is a branch of both theoretical psychology and applied\npsychology that studies human behaviour and experience in complex systems. It is\ninspired by systems theory and systems thinking, and based on the theoretical\nwork of Roger Barker, Gregory Bateson, Humberto Maturana and others. Jeanne\nM. Plas (1986) Systems psychology in the schools. p.xvi It is an approach\nin psychology in which groups and individuals are considered as systems in\nhomeostasis. Alternative terms here are \"systemic psychology\", \"systems\nbehavior\", and \"systems-based psychology\".\n","linknr":475,"url":"Systems_psychology","recorded":1362476972,"links":32,"instances":["psychotherapist","control_theory","control","control_system"],"pdf":["http://www.ctr4process.org/publications/SeminarPapers/28_3%20Process%20Psychology.pdf"],"categories":["Systems psychology|","Applied psychology","Branches of psychology","Systems science"],"headings":["Types of systems psychology","Related fields","See also","References","Further reading","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/00/Complex-adaptive-system.jpg/32px-Complex-adaptive-system.jpg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/4/4a/Commons-logo.svg/30px-Commons-logo.svg.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/vector/images/search-ltr.png?303-4","//bits.wikimedia.org/images/wikimedia-button.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/poweredby_mediawiki_88x31.png"],"tags":[["setpoint","control_system"],["controller","control_theory"],["feed_forward","control"],["michael_white","psychotherapist"]],"members":["michael_white","controller","feed_forward","setpoint"],"related":["Theoretical_psychology","Applied_psychology","Human_behaviour","Experience","Complex_system","Systems_theory","Systems_thinking","Roger_Barker","Gregory_Bateson","Humberto_Maturana","Psychology","Systems","Homeostasis","Eng